    "objective": "“to develop a convenient numerical method which is applicable to the analysis of both data at non-steady state and at steady state with improved computation time using an ordinary and/or the Bayesian weighted nonlinear least-squares method program, MULTI2(Bayes)”",
    "covariates": "Tested: - Included: WT on Vm and Vd",
    "observations": "This article mostly explains the development of a new algorithm for the prediction of michaelis-menten kinetics, using PHT in a few patients as an example. Although the parameter information is not of interest, the developed method does allow full PK simulations without the need for differential equations.",
    "dose": "Steady-state oral doses in patients",
    "structure": "One compartment model with first order absorption and michaelis-menten elimination",
    "equations": "Vm=theta1*WT*exp(eta1) Km=theta2*exp(eta2) Vd=theta3*WT*exp(eta3) Ka=theta4*exp(eta4) dt=t-t(t-1) C’(t-1)=C(t-1)+X(t-1)*(1-exp(-Ka*dt))/Vd Ct=C(t-1)+(X(t-1)*(1-exp(-Ka*dt))/Vd)-0.5*((Vm*C(t-1)*dt)/(Km+C(t-1))+(Vm*C’(t-1)*dt)/(Km+C’(t-1)))/Vd Ct=Cipred Cobs=Cipred The above equation was derived by the authors as a new method for describing concentrations (C) at time t based on michaelis-menten kinetics using a semi-integrated equation. It requires a sufficiently small delta time (dt) to achieve accuracy in its predictions. Xt is the amount in the absorption compartment. C(t-1) is the concentration at the previous timepoint. X(t-1) is the amount in the absorption compartment at the previous timepoint. Note the different use of C and C’ Multiple parameter values were mentioned in the article. Given that the focus is on methodology, one set of parameter values was chosen at random to be listed here.",
    "parameter_values": "theta1=6.8 theta2=3.8 theta3=0.65 theta4=0.5 omega1=0.195 omega2=0.623 omega3=0.592 omega4=1.00",
    "validation": "No/No"
